00:15:18.806 --> 00:15:20.549
We are here to protect each other's growth.

00:15:20.849 --> 00:15:24.715
We voluntarily lay down our rights so that someone else has the space to stand up and grow.

00:15:24.755 --> 00:15:28.882
It is a beautiful, deeply sacrificial way to live, and honestly,

00:15:28.962 --> 00:15:34.981
It is the only way to transform a group of self-interested individuals into a true, functioning body.

00:15:35.262 --> 00:15:35.864
It really is.

00:15:36.165 --> 00:15:41.080
And I want to leave you with a final, provocative thought to mull over as you go about your week.

00:15:41.100 --> 00:15:43.026
Think about the modern world we live in right now.

00:15:43.362 --> 00:15:52.659
Today, the concept of freedom is almost exclusively defined as my absolute right to do whatever I want, whenever I want, regardless of how it affects anyone else.

00:15:52.980 --> 00:15:53.440
Very true.

00:15:53.501 --> 00:15:54.863
It is entirely self-centered.

00:15:55.344 --> 00:16:03.058
But what if practicing this first century voluntary surrender of our own rights is actually the most radical thing we could possibly do?

00:16:03.362 --> 00:16:13.560
How might this quiet loving surrender of our rights be the most counter-cultural witness the church could possibly offer to a society that is literally tearing itself apart over personal rights?

00:16:13.761 --> 00:16:15.003
It's a question worth sitting with.

00:16:15.343 --> 00:16:19.010
True freedom might just be the power to lay our rights down for the sake of love.

00:16:19.471 --> 00:16:20.513
Something to think about.

00:16:21.414 --> 00:16:23.478
Thanks for joining us on this deep dive.
